<section xml:id="sec_plotting_implicit_functions">
  <title>Plotting Implicit Functions</title>
  <p>
    The <c>implicitplot()</c> command can be used to plot implicit functions.
    It requires use of the <c>plots</c> package.
    Unlike the normal <c>plot()</c> command,
    each curve that is being plotted must be in the form of an
    <em>equation</em> of two variables,
    including the <m>=</m> sign.
    Additionally, you must specify an interval for
    <em>both</em> variables.
  </p>
  <aside>
    <p>
      The <c>plots</c> package can be loaded using the <c>with()</c> command.
      This only needs to be loaded once per Maple worksheet and needs to be run each time you open a new or previously closed document.
    </p>
  </aside>
  <p>
        <idx><h>packages</h><h>with</h></idx>
        <idx><h>packages</h><h>plots</h></idx>
  </p>
  <p>
    \begin{maplegroup} \begin{mapleinput} {with(plots): } \end{mapleinput} \end{maplegroup}
  </p>
  <p>
    \begin{maplegroup} \begin{mapleinput} {implicitplot(E, x=-5..5, y=-5..5); }<idx><h>implicit functions</h><h>implicitplot!changing axes</h></idx> \end{mapleinput} \relax \vskip.5\MaplePlotHeight Plot:
    tutorials/figures/Implicit_Functions_and_Graphsplot2d2-eps-converted-to.pdf\vskip.5\MaplePlotHeight \end{maplegroup}
  </p>
  <p>
    Most of the implicit functions used in this lab manual will produce smooth curves when plotted.
    See <xref ref="fig_plotresolution">Figure</xref>
    if your plot appears to have jagged edges.
  </p>
  <aside>
    <p>
          <idx><h>implicit functions</h><h>implicitplot!plot resolution</h></idx>
    </p>
    <p>
